The output grid looks very similar to the input grid, however there are a few notable changes. The orange rectangle object is missing entirely and replaced with black color background tiles. There are now additional colored tiles in the yellow, green and red rectangle objects. These additional tiles look like copies of the interior tiles that existed in the gray object. The yellow, green, and red rectangle objects were the same size as the gray object, which is probably why those interiors changed and the orange object went away. Thus the hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain a background color, probably black. It will also contain some number of rectangle empty bounding box objects, probably each a different color. There will also be a rectangle object that is not empty and contains some number of tiles scattered within it. Some of the empty rectangles may be the exact same size as the rectangle with tiles already in it. In order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid with a few changes. The first change is that any rectangle object that did not match the exact size of the object with interior tiles is effectively removed and replaced with background tiles. The second change is that we must copy the interior pattern to all matching exact size empty rectangle objects, but in the color of that rectangle object. Or put another way, we must eliminate all different sized rectangles, and then copy the interior pattern to all same sized rectangles.
